div.p:
By all these Scriptures it manifestly appears who they are that are persecuted, namely the righteous: ‘he that is born after the Spirit’;
Cf. Gal. 4:29. ‘all that will live godly in Christ Jesus’;
2 Tim. 3:12. they that are ‘passed from death unto life’;
1 John 3:14. those who ‘are not of the world’;
John 15:19. all those who are meek and lowly in heart, that mourn for God, that hunger after his likeness; all that love God and their neighbour, and therefore as they have opportunity do good unto all men.
Gal. 6:10.

4. Let us, thirdly, inquire who are they that persecute them. St. Paul answers, ‘He that is born after the flesh’; everyone who is not ‘born of the Spirit’,
Cf. Gal 4:29. or at least desirous so to be; all that do not at
least labour to ‘live godly in Christ Jesus’;
2 Tim. 3:12. all that are not ‘passed from death unto life’, and consequently cannot ‘love the brethren’;
1 John 3:14. ‘the world’, that is, according to our Saviour’s account, ‘they who know not him that sent me’;
Cf. John 15:21. Ὁ κόσμος as the community of those at enmity with God is a special New Testament usage (cf. 7 in Arndt and Gingrich, Greek-English Lexicon), but it was one of Wesley’s favourites; the notable exception, of course, is in his Notes on John 3:16, 17. Generally, however, he followed the mystical tradition of contemptus mundi (Kempis, De Renty, Law); cf. Nos. 4, Scriptural Christianity, II.5 and n., for Wesley’s comments on ‘saints of the world’; and 22, ‘Sermon on the Mount, II’, II.4 and n., for ‘religion of the world’; see also No. 80, ‘On Friendship with the World’, §5. For Wesley’s satanocratic views about the world, cf. No. 12, ‘The Witness of Our Own Spirit’, §10 and n. they who know not God, even the loving, pardoning God, by the teaching of his own Spirit.
